08192nam a22017775i 9780691246499DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912464997 a10.1515/97806912464992doi  a(DE-B1597)633757  a(OCoLC)1343103884  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a302.23/1qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aBail, Chris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBreaking the Social Media Prism :bHow to Make Our Platforms Less Polarizing /cChris Bail. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b1 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the 2022 Paperback Edition -- t1. The Legend of the Echo Chamber -- t2. Why Not Break Our Echo Chambers? -- t3. What Happens When We Break Them? -- t4. The Social Media Prism -- t5. How the Prism Drives Extremism -- t6. How the Prism Mutes Moderates -- t7. Should I Delete My Account? -- t8. Hacking the Prism -- t9. A Better Social Media -- tAppendix: Research Methods -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA revealing look at how user behavior is powering deep social divisions online—and how we might yet defeat political tribalism on social mediaIn an era of increasing social isolation, platforms like Facebook and Twitter are among the most important tools we have to understand each other. We use social media as a mirror to decipher our place in society but, as Chris Bail explains, it functions more like a prism that distorts our identities, empowers status-seeking extremists, and renders moderates all but invisible. Breaking the Social Media Prism challenges common myths about echo chambers, foreign misinformation campaigns, and radicalizing algorithms, revealing that the solution to political tribalism lies deep inside ourselves.Drawing on innovative online experiments and in-depth interviews with social media users from across the political spectrum, this book explains why stepping outside of our echo chambers can make us more polarized, not less. Bail takes you inside the minds of online extremists through vivid narratives that trace their lives on the platforms and off—detailing how they dominate public discourse at the expense of the moderate majority. Wherever you stand on the spectrum of user behavior and political opinion, he offers fresh solutions to counter political tribalism from the bottom up and the top down. He introduces new apps and bots to help readers avoid misperceptions and engage in better conversations with the other side. Finally, he explores what the virtual public square might look like if we could hit "reset" and redesign social media from scratch through a first-of-its-kind experiment on a new social media platform built for scientific research.Providing data-driven recommendations for strengthening our social media connections, Breaking the Social Media Prism shows how to combat online polarization without deleting our accounts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aAdvertising.  aAmericans.  aBarack Obama.  aBill Clinton.  aBreitbart News.  aBrendan Nyhan.  aBullying.  aBumpus.  aCambridge Analytica.  aCampaign manager.  aComputational social science.  aConspiracy theory.  aCopyright.  aCriticism.  aCulture war.  aDan Ariely.  aDisease.  aDuke University.  aEcho chamber (media).  aEmerging technologies.  aEntrepreneurship.  aExtremism.  aFacebook.  aFake news.  aFamily income.  aField experiment.  aFilter bubble.  aFinding.  aGoogle Search.  aGu